## Epic Workflow (Agent Execution Order)

When implementing an epic, follow this sequence:

### 1. Branch Creation

Branch from the latest `epic/autonomus-implementation` (after pulling) before starting each epic:

```bash
git checkout epic/autonomus-implementation
git pull origin epic/autonomus-implementation
git checkout -b epic/E{n}-{short-description}
# Example: git checkout -b epic/E1-project-scaffold
git push -u origin epic/E{n}-{short-description}
```

### 2. Coding Agent Phase
- Read all tasks from `docs/jira-tickets-json/DB-E{n}-*.json`
- Update `docs/tasks/todo.md` with implementation plan
- Implement each task following IMPLEMENTATION DETAILS
- Handle all EDGE CASES listed in task description
- Commit after each logical unit of work

### 3. Refactor Agent Phase (handoff)
- Run after all Coding Agent tasks complete
- Review for Pydantic schema tightness
- Check for code duplication
- Ensure AgentResultEnvelope consistency
- Verify output sanitization

### 4. Testing Agent Phase (handoff)
- Add tests matching `test_requirements` in task JSON
- Run pytest with coverage
- Add adversarial security tests
- Ensure 80% backend / 75% frontend coverage

### 5. Docs Agent Phase (handoff)
- Update relevant AGENT.md files
- Update docs/PLAN.md with completion status
- Capture learnings in docs/learning/
- Update CHANGELOG if applicable

### 6. Backend Verification Gate (Every Backend Task)

After completing any backend task, run **before marking done or committing**:

```bash
uv run ruff check backend && uv run ruff format backend && uv run mypy backend && uv run pytest
```

All four must pass. Use `uv run ruff check backend --fix` when import sort (`I001`) fails. See `backend/AGENT.md` for details.

### 7. Merge Criteria
- [ ] All tasks in epic marked done
- [ ] Backend verification gate passed (full chain above)
- [ ] All tests pass (`pytest`, `vitest`)
- [ ] Linting passes (`ruff`, `eslint`)
- [ ] Type checking passes (`mypy --strict`, `tsc`)
- [ ] `docs/tasks/todo.md` updated with review section
- [ ] `docs/PLAN.md` shows epic as âś… Completed
- [ ] PR approved and merged to `epic/autonomus-implementation`

### 8. GitHub Actions (Post-Epic)

After merge criteria are met on the epic branch:

1. **Push** the epic branch: `git push -u origin epic/E{n}-{short-description}`
2. **Open PR** with base `epic/autonomus-implementation` and head `epic/E{n}-{short-description}`
3. **Wait for CI** â€” fix failures on the same branch and push again
4. **Merge the PR using a merge commit** â€” do not squash or rebase

After the PR is merged:

```bash
git checkout epic/autonomus-implementation
git pull origin epic/autonomus-implementation
git branch -d epic/E{n}-{short-description}   # delete local epic branch only
```

- **Delete local epic branch:** yes â€” run `git branch -d` after merge
- **Delete remote epic branch:** no â€” leave `origin/epic/E{n}-...` on GitHub

To start the next epic:

```bash
git checkout epic/autonomus-implementation
git pull origin epic/autonomus-implementation
git checkout -b epic/E{n+1}-{short-description}
git push -u origin epic/E{n+1}-{short-description}
```

### 9. Context Checkpoint (Long Sessions)

When context reaches ~75% capacity during epic implementation:

1. Write checkpoint to `docs/tasks/checkpoint.md`
2. Commit WIP: `git commit -m "WIP: checkpoint at DB-{nnn}"`
3. Document next steps clearly
4. New session reads checkpoint and continues

See `docs/EXECUTION-RULES.md` Section 8 for full protocol.

